metadata.name: fx(mash) #104
metadata.description:
fx(mash) is my humble contribution to celebrating #fxhashturnsone

This series is based on a simple algorithm - lines of a random length are drawn on a square grid until the grid is full.

I have added a variety of features based on some of my favorite fxhash projects and a few special guests.

This collection is intentionally diverse and disorderly, that's a nice way of saying I only had a short period of time following the release of Acequia. As a result, some of the outputs might be weird, messy, or even bordering on broken (if you get one of the latter please let me know and I'll reimburse you).

Despite being a bit rough around the edges, I hope fx(mash) reflects some measure of my love for the fxhash community. If you're feeling kind, then perhaps it even harks back to the experimental early days :)

The last year has been an incredible journey, thank you for letting me be a part of our story so far.

Controls (in live view):

- Press [s] to save the current image
- Press [g] to toggle grain
- Press [h] for a high-res output

Beta Controls (in live view, definitely not fully tested):

- Press [p] to start/pause animation
- Press [i] to slow down animation
- Press [o] to speed up animation

All primary sales go to Savepakistan.


Acknowledgements:

fx(mash) uses Gorilla Sun's grain implementation, a big thanks to him and meezwhite for a great article that is well worth supporting https://www.fxhash.xyz/article/all-about-that-grain

metadata.name: Fantasmagoria #96
metadata.description:
ℹ see Phantasmagoria - noun - A dreamlike state where real and imagined elements are blurred together.

💡The work on this series started with an exploration on perceived shapes in a complex generator using noise and randomisation.

👻The deeper I was going into my exploration, the more I encountered scary or spooky iterations.

🧙‍♂️Inspired by the art initiated by Paul Philidor or Étienne-Gaspard Robertson, I decided to explore the creation of alternate, disturbing, undefined forms in the dark.

👋🏻 Personally, Fantasmagoria is a catharcis, and might be the last piece of my "dark" phase. Releasing this project means a lot, not only from the work I've put in it, but from the chapter of my life it closes.

metadata.name: Sansuhwa #34
metadata.description: Once upon a time, in a house in an oriental village, you can see beautiful nature when you look at the window. This painting of nature is called "Sansuhwa." You can see the sun or the moon, the mountains, the sea, and the forest, but sometimes you can only see a part of them. And what you see in the bottom right is the way that Asian painting usually signs paintings. Usually, it is written in Chinese characters, but I made it specially in Korean.

metadata.name: Ghrian #388
metadata.description:
Dutch auction (13/11/9/6/3), with price decreasing every 10 minutes after the start of the auction until 9 tez. Price will then decrease to 6 tez after 2 hours, then to 3 after 12 hours.

A selection of 33 different palettes.

The brush draw is determined by angles, shapes, randomly chosen overdraws, brush sizes and widths, among other things.

- Left arrow = draw in 2125x1375
- Right arrow = draw in 11x17 landscape mode fit to screen height
- Up arrow = draw in 1375x2125
- Down arrow = draw in 11x17 portrait mode fit to screen width
- Enter = draw in full window
- Tab = draw in 1400x1400
- Shift = draw in 1:1 aspect ratio scaled to window height with 5% border on all sides
- Alt = draw in 1:1 aspect ratio scaled to window height with 5% border on all sides (default pixel density)
- Left mouse click = save as a png

Pixel density is set to 2 for all of the options above unless noted otherwise.

Please note that the drawing can take quite a while to run, especially in the full screen modes.

See thread below for additional details:

https://twitter.com/AndwerEric/status/1492619586931413000?s=20&t=N8joIBuTNzYYjmcBex0QJQ
